<TITLE> CID get 3 more months to probe 2004 grenade case </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, Mar 4 (bdnews24.com)  A Dhaka court has given the CID another three months to investigate the case filed under the explosives act in connection with the Aug 21, 2004 grenade attack. Dhaka metropolitan sessions judge ANM Bashirullah on Thursday issued the order on a time-extension motion filed by the Criminal Investigation Department of police. CID's Abdul Kahhar Akand, the investigation officer, filed the petition on Monday for report submission, seeking four more months. Public prosecutor Shah Alam told bdnews24.com after the order that extension was given since investigations were reopened into the 2004 grenade attack on an Awami League rally. Akhand was allowed three months in last October and two months in January. Two cases were originally filed in connection with the grenade attack, one for killings and the other for use of explosives. On October 14 last year the cases were transferred to the metropolitan sessions judge's court and the CID was given another extension. The case filed for killings is now pending with the second additional metropolitan sessions judge's court of Fazila Begum. At least 24 people, including Awami League leader Ivy Rahman, wife of president Zillur Rahman, lost their lives in the attack on August 21 on Bangabandhu Avenue in Dhaka. Scores sustained injuries, including prime minister Sheikh Hasina, who was then opposition leader. Investigators, during the previous BNP administration, are accused of attempting to derail the case through different means including recording of false statements from witnesses. After BNP's tenure was over, new investigators, appointed during the regime of the subsequent interim government, pressed charges against 22 people on June 11 last year. BNP leader Nasiruddin Ahmed Pintu and militant outfit Jama'atul Mujahideen, Bangladesh leader Mufti Hannan were among the accused. BNP's former state minister for home, Lutfozzaman Babar, now in jail, was also recently shown arrested in connection with the gre